description:
Watch the Mission Trailer for Ranger's Path: National Park Simulator, a park ranger simulation management game developed by To-Go Games. Players can get a feel for what encounters they'll be faced with as the Park Ranger of a National Park, from clearing storm damage, setting traps, and serving the public. Ranger's Path: National Park Simulator is launching into Early Access for PC (Steam and Epic Games Store).

Don't miss the Reveal Teaser Trailer for Gachiakuta: The Game (working title), an upcoming action RPG based on the beloved anime series developed by Com2uS. Players will become engrossed in the anime’s setting and atmosphere as players fight through monster-infested zones, complete missions, and return safely to secure areas. Gachiakuta: The Game (working title) is coming soon to PlayStation 5 (PS5), Xbox, and PC.

author: IGN
description:
Okay, let’s get this out of the way: we have no idea what we’re talking about when it comes to baseball, sports in general, or even video games about sports (baseball, or otherwise) but considering MLB The Show 25 was one of PlayStation’s few first-party releases of the year, we figured it’s worth discussing. What could the next installment possible add that would liven up the experience enough to get even the most sports-averse of us interested? Explosions? Fireworks? More fireworks? Like, dangerous fireworks? Karaoke? Mascot fights? Sports teams made up of literal versions of whatever they’re named after, like Blue Jays, Diamondbacks, or a variety of different colored socks? Again, we have no idea what we’re talking about here, but when has that stopped us from having fun? Beyond and Happy New Year! 

This weeks show is Hosted by Max Scoville, Brian Altano, Jada Griffin, Nick Maillet, and is produced by Nick Maillet. 

#MLBTheShow #PS5 #PlayStation6
title: MLB The Show 26 Needs To Make Baseball More Dangerous - Beyond Clips

author: IGN
description:
This review contains spoilers for Fallout Season 2, Episode 3, “The Profligate,” which is available to stream now on Prime Video. 

Civil wars are erupting all over the wasteland in Fallout Season 2’s third chapter, and in the middle of it all are two men making hugely important decisions that will shape their destinies. While it’s a shame that Lucy had to be put in crucifixion time-out for most of this episode, and Robert House’s not-so-mysterious identity continues to be a sticking point, this is an otherwise fantastic, character-driven episode that thrives on bringing important elements from the New Vegas video game into the spotlight. It’s packed with so much good stuff that I didn’t even get to mention Victor the Securitron’s guest appearance, but I’m sure you’re as pleased as me that he’s still rolling around the Mojave.

#IGN #Fallout
title: Fallout Season 2, Episode 3 Review
